nses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image shows \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal gastric mucosa\u003C/strong\u003E with its characteristic layers and organisation. The surface epithelium consists of columnar mucous cells, which lead into gastric pits (foveolae). These pits extend into the gastric glands containing various specialised cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis is not \u003Cstrong\u003Eintestinal metaplasia\u003C/strong\u003E, which would show goblet cells and intestinal-type epithelium. \u003Cstrong\u003EChronic gastritis\u003C/strong\u003E would demonstrate inflammatory cell infiltration and mucosal damage. \u003Cstrong\u003EGastric adenocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E would show dysplastic cells with altered architecture. \u003Cstrong\u003EGastric ulceration\u003C/strong\u003E would show a breach in the mucosa extending into deeper layers with associated inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The gastric mucosa consists of surface mucous cells, gastric pits, and gastric glands containing multiple specialised cell types.","Normal gastric mucosa shows a characteristic organisation with surface epithelium, gastric pits (foveolae), and underlying glands."],"references":["Hsu M, Safadi AO, Lui F. Physiology, Stomach. [Updated 2023 Jul 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK535425/","Bartuzi Z, Gawro\u0144ska-Ukleja E, Roma\u0144ski B. Macroscopic picture of gastric mucosa in endoscopic examination of patients with chronic gastritis and food allergy. Med Sci Monit. 2000 Nov-Dec;6(6):1203-8. PMID: 11208480.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"ty